The European Green Deal
NEW YORK – Europe has done it.
The "Green Pact for Europe" announced by the European Commission is to date the first global sustainable development plan decided by a major region of the planet.
It thereby becomes a benchmark for the entire world – a guide to transforming towards a prosperous, socially inclusive, and environmentally sustainable economy, a first agenda, for everyone's use, to achieve it.
Of course, the task awaiting Europeans is impressive.
Even the reading of the documents that have just been made public is so: a plethora at first glance of plans, consultations, regulatory frameworks, laws, budgets, and diplomacy, a large number of involved and interconnected subjects, ranging from energy to transportation, from food to industry.
Its detractors will mock European bureaucracy.
It is a bureaucracy in the best Weberian sense of the term: it is rational.
The "objectives of sustainable development are clearly stated, the targets are defined in accordance with objectives subject to a deadline, and the programs and procedures are adapted to the targets."
The ambition displayed is to achieve "carbon neutrality" (net zero emissions of greenhouse gases) by 2050, to establish a circular economy that puts an end to the destructive pollution caused by plastics and other petrochemical derivatives, pesticides, and toxic waste, to establish a food system "from farm to table," that does not kill people by making them eat overly processed products of the industry, nor kill the earth with unsustainable agricultural practices.
And the European Commission understands that the method to achieve this must rely on the citizens themselves.
Its detractors will again view the announcements of public consultations as empty rhetoric for dreamers.
But let's talk about pointless chatter with French President Emmanuel Macron, who faced over a year of riots sparked by protests, or Chilean President Sebastián Piñera, whose country suddenly rose up last autumn after a slight increase in subway ticket prices.
French President Macron and Chilean President Piñera are both convinced of the need for ecological change.
Both have committed their countries to carbon neutrality by 2050.
And both are desperately trying to figure out how to organize or structure a public consultation, but after the fact.
American neoliberal supporters will once again mock and claim that the "market" will know how to remedy climate change.
But it's enough to look at the United States today.
If neoliberalism treats the planet the way it has treated American infrastructure, we all have reason to be concerned.
Arriving at an American airport means having to deal with broken elevators, malfunctioning escalators, shuttles that don't work, taxis that don't show up, non-existent rail connections, highways with roads in such poor condition that you can't drive on them, and detours instead.
The reason for these dysfunctions is simple: corruption.
Each American election cycle now costs around $8 billion, if not more, and it is funded by billionaires, large oil companies, the military-industrial complex, the healthcare industry lobby, and groups determined to lower taxes and protect the status quo at all costs.
The solutions offered by the market are a joke when politics is subject to all the influences that stem from it, as is the case in the United States.
The European Green Deal demonstrates a government as it should be and not a government subservient to corporate interests.
The European Green Deal indeed demonstrates the success of European social democracy (in its operational and non-partisan sense).
A mixed economy, combining markets, state regulatory power, the public sector, and civil society, will pursue a mixed strategy: public objectives, public investments in infrastructure, private investments in industrial transformation, research and development missions based on public-private partnerships, and an informed population.
In fact, it is one of the most sophisticated industrial policies at this level.
(In these broad outlines, I recently indicated what a social-democratic Green New Deal strategy would look like for the United States.)
We have reason to be optimistic.
The most crucial point is that advanced technologies, which will enable the creation of a decarbonized, resource-efficient, and thus ecologically sustainable advanced economy, already exist in the commercial or pre-commercial stage.
By combining renewable energy, digital technologies, cutting-edge materials, and collaborative economies in transportation or other infrastructure, we can decarbonize the energy system, transition to a circular economy, and drastically reduce primary resource flows.
However, we must overcome three major challenges.
The first is to overcome the interests that seek to maintain the status quo.
The major oil companies will have to absorb the losses, but workers in the sector and mining regions should receive compensation, in the form of income support, retraining through education, and other public aid.
The European plan rightfully claims a "just transition".
The second challenge is that of financing.
The European Union, like other regions of the world, will have to reorient a relatively small portion of its production, from 1% to 2%, towards a green economy, particularly for new infrastructure, public markets, research and development, industrial equipment renewal, etc. Financing will come from the private sector, but also from public budgets.
The European Union must stand up to ideologues who oppose an increase in EU spending.
The facts must be taken into account.
The last major challenge is diplomatic.
The European Union represents approximately 9.1% of global carbon dioxide emissions, while China accounts for 30% and the United States for 14%.
Even if the European Union manages to implement its green pact in its entirety, it will be for naught if the other regions of the world do not join it in its fight.
European leaders therefore rightfully consider diplomacy to be fundamental in the success of the green pact.
Let's take the example of China.
After decades of rapid growth, which have eliminated mass poverty, China has become the world's largest CO2 emitter (although its per capita emissions remain two times lower than those of the United States).
China, alone, will determine the future of the global climate.
On the one hand, Chinese leaders know that their country is extremely vulnerable to climate change and risks diplomatic isolation if it doesn't make enough efforts to decarbonize; on the other hand, they must face the dangers of the unfortunate Cold War launched by America.
Hardliners within the government and Chinese coal lobbies resist, under pressure from the United States, the decarbonization, especially since Trump rejects it himself.
European diplomacy can make a difference if it refuses to subscribe to America's insidious measures to constrain China and instead offers China a positive and unambiguous partnership: working together to establish sustainable infrastructure, development, and technology in Eurasia, as part of a Chinese Green Deal comparable to the European model.
A partnership of this kind would be of immense benefit to Europe, China, and the dozen Eurasian countries that separate them, not to mention the world at large.
The European Union has made a historic step with its ambitious, mobilizing, and achievable plan.
The Green Deal is a powerful beacon of hope in a world of uncertainty and instability.
